From: aiopquic build <build@aiopquic.local>
Subject: [PATCH] picoquic: drop system <linux/io_uring.h> include in sockloop.c

picoquic's sockloop.c includes <linux/io_uring.h> from the kernel
uapi (linux-libc-dev) immediately before <liburing.h>. Both headers
share the same include guard (LINUX_IO_URING_H), so whichever is
included first wins and the other is silently skipped.

On systems whose linux-libc-dev is older than liburing's bundled
copy (e.g. Ubuntu 22.04 ships 5.15-era uapi), the system header
wins and the newer types/enums referenced by liburing.h inline
functions (struct io_uring_buf_ring, IORING_OP_MSG_RING,
IORING_FILE_INDEX_ALLOC, IORING_OP_SOCKET, IORING_SETUP_CQE32, …)
are undefined, producing dozens of compile errors.

liburing.h already pulls in its bundled liburing/io_uring.h, which
is a strict superset of the kernel uapi. Dropping the explicit
<linux/io_uring.h> include lets the bundled header define the
LINUX_IO_URING_H guard with full definitions.

This patch is local to aiopquic so we can build against arbitrary
liburing versions without depending on the host's kernel header age.
---
 picoquic/sockloop.c | 1 -
 1 file changed, 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/picoquic/sockloop.c b/picoquic/sockloop.c
--- a/picoquic/sockloop.c
+++ b/picoquic/sockloop.c
@@ -79,7 +79,6 @@
 #include <netinet/in.h>

 #if defined(PICOQUIC_WITH_IO_URING)
-#include <linux/io_uring.h>
 #include <liburing.h>
 #else
 #ifndef PICOQUIC_USES_SELECT
